news.title: Nashik civic body serves notices to three lakh property tax defaulters
news.para: The Nashik Municipal Corporation (NMC) has issued notices to over 3 lakh property tax defaulters, who collectively owe Rs 400 crore. These defaulters have 15 days to clear their dues, which have accumulated over the past one to six years.

news.title: MDDA cracks down on illegal plotting across over 150 bighas in Dehradun region
news.para: The Mussoorie Dehradun Development Authority (MDDA) has intensified its crackdown on illegal land activities, reclaiming over 150 bighas of illegally plotted land in the past month. The authority also sealed numerous unauthorized multi-story buildings across areas like Bhaniyawala, Haridwar Bypass Road, and Rishikesh.

news.title: No registry or power: How Ghaziabad development body plans to check illegal colonies
news.para: Ghaziabad Development Authority seeks to halt property registrations in unauthorized colonies to curb their growth, citing a recent survey revealing a significant increase. This directive clashes with existing registration laws, but GDA argues it's supported by a 2024 Supreme Court order concerning unauthorized constructions and the necessity of completion certificates for essential services.

news.title: Bengaluru: No OC needed for 1,200 sq ft homes; government eases rules for small plots
news.para: The Karnataka government has exempted individual houses on 30x40 sites (1,200 sqft) within Greater Bengaluru Authority limits from needing an occupancy certificate (OC). This decision, announced Tuesday, applies to ground-plus-two or stilt-plus-three floor constructions. The move aims to reduce red tape for smaller residential projects following concerns about mandatory OCs.

news.title: No government nod, 32 flats razed by Gurugram civic body
news.para: Gurugram authorities cracked down on illegal construction in Anamika Enclave, Sector 14, demolishing and sealing 32 unauthorized flats. The buildings lacked mandatory map approval from MCG and fire safety NOCs, including essential fire escape doors. MCG officials emphasized their commitment to preventing illegal construction, highlighting the strain it places on city infrastructure and services.

news.title: Redevelopment of housing societies in Mumbai to add supply homes worth ₹1.3 lakh crore: Report
news.para: Mumbai's housing society redevelopment is set to surge, adding over 44,000 new homes by 2030, valued at Rs 1.3 lakh crore. Since 2020, 910 societies have signed redevelopment agreements, unlocking significant land. Western Suburbs will see the most growth, while the state government anticipates substantial revenue from these projects.

news.title: Bhubaneswar's new city project gets cabinet nod
news.para: The Odisha cabinet has approved the development of a 'New City' near Bhubaneswar, spanning 800 acres. With a projected investment of Rs 8,179 crore over 15 years, the project aims to create a multi-economic growth zone aligned with Viksit Odisha 2036. The city will prioritize public transport, affordable housing, and cutting-edge infrastructure, including innovation hubs and green spaces.

news.title: Mumbai: BMC releases proposed ESZ plan for SGNP
news.para: Draft management plan lists 184.5 hectares of slums, quarries, and ready-mix plants as threats, yet leaves scope for industries and real estate to come up

news.title: Commercial use of properties along 42 major roads to be allowed in Prayagraj
news.para: Prayagraj has implemented its Master Plan 2031, permitting commercial activities along 42 major roads, including Mahatma Gandhi Marg and Tashkent Marg. This expansion from the previous plan, which only covered 29 roads, allows buildings up to two floors to be used for commercial purposes. The Prayagraj Development Authority will conduct surveys and enforce compounding rules to ensure compliance.

news.title: Lucknow development body property worth ₹300 crore sold in e-auction
news.para: Lucknow Development Authority's recent e-auction generated over Rs 300 crore through the sale of various properties. The auction included school plots in Basantkunj, a commercial plot in the Central Business District, and residential plots in Gomtinagar Extension. High participation, driven by publicity and site visits, indicates strong investor confidence in Lucknow's real estate market.

news.title: Noida authority to raze 60 buildings with flats sold for up to ₹65 lakh
news.para: Noida Authority initiated a demolition drive in Salarpur Khadar village, targeting approximately 60 illegally constructed buildings erected by 39 developers on 24 plots. While some demolitions were halted due to court stay orders, authorities razed structures on three plots and are preparing actions against developers under land mafia law.

news.title: Ground coverage cap set to go with Noida bylaws set for major overhaul
news.para: The Uttar Pradesh government plans to unify building bylaws for Noida, Greater Noida, and YEIDA, aiming to boost investment and simplify construction rules. The new regulations propose scrapping ground coverage limits, increasing floor area ratio (FAR), and relaxing setback norms. These changes will encourage vertical growth, streamline approvals, and make projects more viable across the region.

news.title: RBI signs ₹3,472 crore land deal with MMRCL for Nariman Point plot to build new office complex
news.para: In a significant transaction, the Reserve Bank of India acquired a 4.2-acre plot in Nariman Point from Mumbai Metro Rail Corporation for ₹3,472 crore to construct its new office complex. This deal, significantly above market rates, led to the withdrawal of a public auction, marking a rare instance in the area's history.

news.title: CAG flags under-utilisation of welfare fund for construction workers
news.para: A CAG audit reveals that Gujarat collected over Rs 4,700 crore in welfare cess from developers over 16 years, but only utilized Rs 808 crore for worker welfare. The unspent funds are attributed to the non-constitution of a Welfare Fund and a single-member board lacking employer and worker representatives.

news.title: Britain's Vistry warns of challenges after interim profit drop
news.para: Vistry's first-half profit plummeted by 33.2% due to economic uncertainties and persistent inflation, impacting buyer affordability and delaying interest rate cuts. The British homebuilder anticipates government housing support to drive future contracts, but concerns over potential tax hikes and slow public sector funding deployment temper optimism. Shares have significantly declined amid challenging market conditions, particularly in London.

news.title: Limited strategic synergy in Vedanta's JAL acquisition; deal rated credit negative: CreditSights
news.para: CreditSights views Vedanta's proposed Rs 17,000 crore acquisition of Jaiprakash Associates Ltd (JAL) as credit negative, citing limited strategic synergies and JAL's heavy debt. The acquisition exposes Vedanta to cyclical real estate, cement, and infrastructure segments, posing execution risks. S&P Global Ratings also notes the diversification into unrelated businesses could weaken Vedanta's position and pressure leverage.

news.title: ED seizes luxury vehicles in Goa 'illegal' land grab case
news.para: The Enforcement Directorate (ED) has seized luxury cars and cash following raids in Goa and Hyderabad, related to a Rs 1,200 crore land grabbing case. Accused individuals, including Yeshwant Sawant, allegedly used forged documents to illegally acquire prime Communidade lands. The investigation aims to uncover a broader network involved in illegal land grabbing across Goa.

news.title: GST revamp to reduce cement prices by ₹30-35 per bag: Ind-Ra
news.para: The GST Council's decision to reduce the tax on cement from 28% to 18% is expected to lower cement prices by Rs 30-35 per 50 kg bag, benefiting consumers and infrastructure projects. While this revamp is a structural positive for the cement sector, overall demand growth is projected to be 5-7%.

news.title: Jharkhand HC stays auction of sand ghats over PESA rules non-compliance
news.para: The Jharkhand High Court has halted the auction of sand ghats and the issuance of mining leases for minor minerals due to the non-implementation of PESA Rules. This decision follows a contempt petition filed by the Adiwasi Buddhijeevi Manch, citing non-compliance with a previous court order.

news.title: Chandigarh: Ongoing VB probe casts shadow on Manimajra housing project
news.para: Chandigarh's Municipal Corporation faces scrutiny over a high-value housing project in Manimajra due to the absence of a formal policy for allocating 15% of units to the Economically Weaker Section, as mandated. This comes amid a Vigilance investigation into the Uppal Housing Society's failure to construct EWS houses.
